<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF207-420-732  </DOCNO><DOCID>07 420 732.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Electronic Engineering Times  July 10 1989 n546 p1(2).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>Philips has digital tape copy guard.andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Doherty, Richard.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>A new copy-protection scheme proposed by NV Phillips could makedigital audio tape (DAT) units available in the US by the fall of1989.andP;  The system, called Solocopy, stores ID and subcode dataunique to each CD title in nonvolatile memory and thwarts attemptsto copy CDs onto DAT more than once on the same deck.andP;  Phillipshas not yet released full details of the technology used, but thescheme will require some hardware modification to DAT decks.andO;Representatives of the International Federation of Phonogram andVideogram Producers recently previewed Solocopy, and agreed thatshipments of DAT decks could begin as soon as the protection is inplace if the Recording Industry Association of America alsoapproves the technique.andP;  A previous anti-copy scheme, CBS Labs'Copycode, had been rejected by the National Bureau of Standards.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     Digital Audio TapeCopy Prevention TechniquesTape StorageInternational TradeNew Technique.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>